This may not be the proper group to post such a question, but what the heck...

I know ASCII can store 128 characters because it's defined with 7 bits     
(ie: 2^7 = 128).

I heard that another code called TTS can store 100 characters within only
6 bits. As 2^6 only gives 64, there must be some special encoding or
compression to achieve this result. Can someone explain me how this TTS
code works?

Thanks.

	Marc

